Regardless of what 
\begin_inset Formula $x\cdot z$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{\lambda\rightarrow\infty}\left\Vert y_{\lambda}\right\Vert ^{2}$
\end_inset

 doesn't exist and hence, by contradiction 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is unbounded.
 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}=\left\{ 0\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Then take 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in C$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z,\lambda$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x+\lambda z\in C$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert z\right\Vert _{2}=1$
\end_inset

