\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x+\lambda z\in C$
\end_inset

) and if 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 were unbounded for any such 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 would be a recession direction.
 Note 
\begin_inset Formula $x+\lambda z$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

farthest
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 point in 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 If there were some other point 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in C$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert y-x\right\Vert _{2}>\left\Vert x+\lambda z\right\Vert _{2}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{'}=\frac{\left(y-x\right)}{\left\Vert y-x\right\Vert _{2}}$
\end_inset

 would have been a direction considered (since 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is convex and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $x+\lambda\left(y-x\right)=\lambda y+\left(1-\lambda\right)x\in C$
\end_inset

).
